        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-08-11T08:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-08-11T08:23:00-05:00" n="205"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d205">
                <head>205. Telegram 12672 From the Embassy in the Soviet Union to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d205fn1">
                        <p>
                            <seg type="summary">Summary: The Embassy reported on an August 10 dinner
                                conversation between the Embassy’s Political Counselor and Deputy
                                Chief of the International Organizations Department of the Soviet
                                Ministry of Foreign Affairs <persName corresp="#p_TRM_1"
                                    >Timerbayev</persName>, which concerned the recent Soviet
                                nuclear explosions.</seg>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <seg type="source">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1"
                                    >RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D760309–0904.
                                Confidential. Repeated for information to the consulate in
                                Leningrad.</seg>
                        </p>
                    </note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1976-08-11T13:23:00+00:00">August 11, 1976, 1323Z</date>.</dateline>
                <p>12672. Subj: Soviet Nuclear Explosions.</p>
                <p>1. During brief conversation at dinner August 10, Political Counselor asked
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TRM_1">Roland Timerbayev</persName>, Deputy
                    Head International Organizations Division, <gloss target="#t_MFA_1">MFA</gloss>,
                    about two recent Soviet nuclear explosions which press reports allege may have
                    exceeded TTBT and <gloss target="#t_PNE_1">PNE</gloss> threshold. In reply,
                        <persName corresp="#p_TRM_1">Timerbayev</persName> said that his government
                    was in the process of issuing a press statement through the Soviet Embassy in
                    Washington which would clarify this matter. Press statement would assert flatly
                    that Soviets have not exceeded limits imposed by treaty.</p>
                <p>2. When asked whether one of explosions was a <gloss target="#t_PNE_1"
                        >PNE</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_TRM_1">Timerbayev</persName> replied
                    that one of these explosions clearly did not take place at the <pb facs="0680"
                        n="646" xml:id="pg_646"/> traditional nuclear testing site and that the
                    conclusion to be drawn from this is clear. In essence, this was meant as
                    confirmation that one explosion was indeed a <gloss target="#t_PNE_1"
                        >PNE</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_SWJ_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1">Stoessel</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
